<Infographic
  title="Protocol stack and architectural principles"
  description="The quantum-internet protocol stack: RFC 9340's architectural principles, the layered stacks proposed by Wehner 2018, Van Meter 2014, and Dahlberg 2019, and the deliberately deferred concerns (naming, addressing, routing) that the standardisation track has left open."
  references={[
    "dahlberg-sigcomm-2019",
    "kozlowski-rfc9340",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "meter-ieee-2014",
    "wehner-science-2018",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="protocols" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Protocol stack and architectural principles</h1>
        <p>
          A quantum-internet protocol stack faces design constraints that don't appear in
          the classical TCP/IP stack: no-cloning forbids store-and-forward retransmission,
          the link-layer service delivers an entangled resource rather than a bit
          stream, and the network has to coordinate two-way classical communication
          alongside the quantum channel. RFC 9340 is the IRTF's informational
          consolidation of how to think about these — the canonical reference for the
          architecture <SourceNote id="kozlowski-rfc9340" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          This page covers RFC 9340's architectural principles, the three layered-stack
          proposals that inform it (Wehner 2018, Van Meter 2014, Dahlberg 2019), the
          link-layer service the rest of the stack rests on, and the concerns the
          standardisation track has deliberately deferred.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="rfc9340" data-nav-section>
        <h2>RFC 9340 principles</h2>
        <p>
          RFC 9340 defines the link-layer service as <q>deliver Bell pair (A, B) on
          demand</q> between two named endpoints, at adequate fidelity. Everything else
          — teleportation, key extraction, distributed computing — is built on top of
          that primitive at higher layers <SourceNote id="kozlowski-rfc9340" />. The
          document is informational rather than a wire-protocol standard; it names
          requirements, layer boundaries, and a vocabulary, but does not specify on-wire
          formats.
        </p>
        <p>
          Three principles worth flagging:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Bell pair as the network resource.</strong> The network's product is
            entanglement, not bits. Applications consume Bell pairs; the network's success
            metric is entanglement-delivery rate × fidelity, not bandwidth.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Classical co-routing.</strong> Every quantum protocol requires a
            classical side-channel for measurement results, corrections, and heralding
            signals. The classical channel is in-band with the quantum service; the stack
            schedules both.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Deferred concerns.</strong> Naming, addressing, and routing are
            acknowledged as open and not standardised. The document calls these out so
            implementations don't accidentally invent incompatible solutions.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="stacks" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Layered stacks compared</h2>
        <p>
          Three influential layered-stack proposals precede or accompany RFC 9340:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Van Meter 2014</strong> — the earliest comprehensive proposal. Five
            layers (physical, link, network, transport, application) mapping
            classical-TCP/IP structure onto a quantum context, with entanglement
            generation and purification at the link / network boundary
            <SourceNote id="meter-ieee-2014" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Wehner 2018</strong> — Frames the quantum internet as a five-stage
            roadmap of capabilities (trusted-node QKD → prepare-and-measure → entanglement
            distribution → quantum memory → fault-tolerant) rather than a strict layered
            stack; each stage unlocks a class of applications. The protocol-stack view is
            implicit but the stages are the operational reference points
            <SourceNote id="wehner-science-2018" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Dahlberg 2019</strong> — A concrete protocol design for the link
            layer specifically: an Entanglement Generation Protocol (EGP) that requests
            on-demand pair generation, and a Distributed-Queue Protocol (DQP) that
            schedules competing requests across two nodes
            <SourceNote id="dahlberg-sigcomm-2019" />. Implemented on the NV-centre stack
            at Delft.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          RFC 9340 sits above this work, consolidating the architectural principles
          without prescribing a specific wire protocol. Kumar 2025 §4.5 surveys all three
          together <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="link-layer" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The link layer</h2>
        <p>
          The link-layer service in a quantum network has two responsibilities: generate
          Bell pairs on demand between adjacent nodes, and report success or failure
          with the necessary metadata (fidelity, heralding outcome, Pauli correction).
          The Dahlberg EGP design specifies a request-response interface — an application
          asks for a Bell pair with a target fidelity, and the EGP either delivers one
          and reports the outcome or reports a failure with diagnostic
          state <SourceNote id="dahlberg-sigcomm-2019" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          Above the link layer, two consumers dominate today: the application layer
          (teleportation, QKD, distributed-compute primitives), and the network layer
          (multi-hop swapping to extend entanglement beyond a single link). The covered
          subjects — teleportation, swapping, distribution — sit at this interface.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="open" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What's deliberately deferred</h2>
        <p>
          RFC 9340 names several concerns as open and unstandardised:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Naming and addressing.</strong> How a node identifies itself or names
            its counterparties is unspecified. Classical analogues (IP addresses, DNS
            names) may not map cleanly because the network resource is a Bell pair, not a
            destination IP.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Routing.</strong> Which path to take across a quantum-repeater
            network is an active research area. Multi-hop swapping introduces fidelity
            decay that path-selection algorithms have to account for; classical
            shortest-path is not the answer.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Heterogeneity.</strong> Two endpoints may run different qubit
            modalities (transmon ↔ NV centre, for example), and the entanglement
            generation that connects them must bridge their photonic encodings and
            wavelengths. The protocol layer carries the heterogeneity question.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          These are intentional deferrals — the standardisation track preferred to nail
          down architectural principles before locking in concrete protocols whose
          numbers would change as the hardware evolves. Future RFCs and protocol drafts
          will fill in these layers as the platforms mature.
        </p>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
